--The where clause is super important. If you execute without it, the whole table gets updated unintentionally and wipes out the data that was there before

DELETE
DELETE FROMtable_name
WHERE <condition>
Delete is for data hygiene to remove inactive users or users that opted out, test data 
You need the where clause to specify what to delete. Without it,t everything will get wiped out, 
soft delete, you still have a copy, hard delete gone forever 
DELETE FROM leads
WHERE last_open < 2023-12-31

TRUNCATE removes data but does not remove the table; it is to make space for new data before insert 
often used in the medallion system to insert clean data 
TRUNCATE silver.customers_table;
INSERT INTO silver.customers_table
( id, UPPER(TRIMM(full_name)), address,)
FROM bronze.customers_table;
Truncate is faster than delete
